</p>
<p>When you do</p>
<p>motor.set(ControlMode.Position, position)</p>
<p>that position is in terms of encoder counts/ticks. You need a way to zero out your encoders. One way is to manually move them down with phoenix tuner while the robot is enabled in test mode as test mode should disable your commands and subsystems or another way would be to mechanically move it down and then power cycle the robot and just reset your encoders on startup to 0.</p>
<p>You can get the current encoder position by taking a self test snapshot in phoenix tuner or by simply displaying the data on SmartDashboard with motor.getSelectedSensorPosition(). For how to actually implement the different “levels” you could look at how we did it in our code.</p>
